{
  "answer": "**\"Goristan-e-Shahi\" (The Royal Graveyard), Chapter 9 of *Bang-E-Dara Part 3* by Allama Iqbal, is a reflective poem contemplating the ruins, tombs, and history of the royal graveyard—likely the historic site in Aurangabad housing Nizam Shahi tombs.**[^1]\n\nThe poem richly describes the desolate atmosphere, fallen kings' tombs (\"A graveyard, yes, but dust of high degree, / A fallen nation’s final treasury\" [p-49c46c]), their past glory (\"In this dark grave, those suns of glory lie, / Before whose gates once bowed the very sky\" [p-04f912]), Death's inevitability, and national sorrow (\"Our hearts are filled with memories of the past, / This nation’s love for its lost kings will last\" [p-f20096]). However, it contains **no lines where Iqbal (or a first-person narrator) explicitly walks, strolls, or moves among the royal tombs**. The perspective is observational and meditative, without personal locomotion described.[^1][^2]\n\nIf you're recalling a different poem, prose reflection, or secondary source about Iqbal's visit (e.g., his travels), it's not present here. The full English translation is available in the cited chapter.[^1]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 3*, [Chapter 9: Goristan-e-Shahi (translation)](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-3-cc61e8/09-goristan-e-shahi/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Searches for phrases like \"walks among,\" \"royal tombs,\" \"tombs royal,\" and \"walks tombs\" across the English corpus returned zero matches, confirming the absence.",
